00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:39.169
it's moderately big.

00:08:39.169 --> 00:08:40.816
KATHRYN HURLEY: Moderately
big?

00:08:40.816 --> 00:08:43.490
It sounds pretty big to me.

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:47.260
And so that brings up
a good question.

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:49.390
A hot topic right
now is big data.

00:08:49.390 --> 00:08:51.930
And I know you have an opinion
about big data because I

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:54.860
watched some of your talks.

00:08:54.860 --> 00:08:57.160
What do you think
about big data?

00:08:57.160 --> 00:08:59.650
HILARY MASON: So I think the
term "big data" is a little

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:02.100
difficult because it's
so hard to define.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:05.220
So some people think big
data is when it won't

00:09:05.220 --> 00:09:06.500
fit in Excel anymore.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:08.960
And some people think big data
is when you need more than one

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:13.180
node to actually operate over
something or store it.

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:16.240
What I think is actually
fundamentally new and

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:22.220
interesting about big data is
that it reduces the friction

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:23.280
to working with data.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:26.040
So it lets you ask a question
and get the answer back before

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:28.500
you've forgotten why you've
asked that question in the

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.360
first place.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:34.840
So I think the advantages to
using these big-data type

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:38.330
technologies are really
human advantages.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:41.240
They're not so much technical
advantages.

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:44.730
And I also, every so often, find
myself at a conference

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:48.650
with astrophysicists or people
who work in bioinformatics.

00:09:48.650 --> 00:09:50.790
And they look at our data,
and they say, ha.

00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:51.750
You thought that was big.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:55.490
We had to invent a new kind of
hard drive to store our stuff.

00:09:55.490 --> 00:09:57.400
So those are the people
who are really pushing

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:01.300
the edge of big data.

00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:02.310
KATHRYN HURLEY: And so it
sounded like you have a couple

00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:05.630
tools that you like to use
to work with big data.

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:08.130
Can you share what some
of those are?

00:10:08.130 --> 00:10:10.720
HILARY MASON: Sure, though
they're fairly embarrassing

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:12.280
and old-fashioned.

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:15.110
My favorite way to work with
data whenever possible is on

00:10:15.110 --> 00:10:19.840
the command line using the bash
tools, so grep and awk.

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:22.570
If you look on bitly's GitHub
page, we actually have some

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:26.340
nice scripts you can run to do
histograms on the command line

00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:29.970
and do some really basic
sampling and get a sense of

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:31.900
your data just from that.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:33.970
That's not always possible,
though, so I'm

00:10:33.970 --> 00:10:35.510
a huge Python nerd.

00:10:35.510 --> 00:10:38.810
We use NumPy, SciPy,
and scikit-learn.

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:42.092
We also do have a Hadoop
cluster here at bitly.

00:10:42.092 --> 00:10:44.370
It's not my favorite piece
of infrastructure,

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:46.230
but we do use it.

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:49.020
And it works very well for
what we use it for.

00:10:49.020 --> 00:10:49.280
KATHRYN HURLEY: Cool.

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:50.960
Thanks for sharing.

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:51.770
HILARY MASON: Of course.

00:10:51.770 --> 00:10:54.280
KATHRYN HURLEY: And so working
with all this data, you

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:56.480
probably have a lot of insights,
make a lot of

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:59.420
interesting discoveries
with this data.

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:02.770
Can you share what your most
interesting discovery is with

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:04.350
all the bitly data?

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:07.740
HILARY MASON: It's really
hard to pick just one.

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:11.480
But one thing we put up on our
blog today was we looked at

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:13.990
the half-life of content
by topic.

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:18.220
And it turns out that most
content actually has very

00:11:18.220 --> 00:11:19.550
similar half-lives.

00:11:19.550 --> 00:11:22.590
And a half-life is the time it
takes for a link to get half

00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:24.410
the clicks it'll ever get.

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:27.880
So just sort of looking at
how attention to it is

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:29.230
modified over time.

00:11:29.230 --> 00:11:31.060
But one kind of content is much

00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:33.640
shorter, and that's sports.

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:39.490
So once sports news is out of
date, nobody cares about it.

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:40.190
APRIL ANDERSON: That's
a point.

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:42.220
That's very true.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:44.460
HILARY MASON: Not really a
surprise, but good to see it

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:45.630
proven in the data.

00:11:45.630 --> 00:11:47.180
KATHRYN HURLEY: That's
so cool.

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:50.420
And you make these discoveries,
but how do they

00:11:50.420 --> 00:11:52.930
actually influence bitly
as a product?

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:56.560
Do you see any changes in the
UI or in the back end?

00:11:56.560 --> 00:11:59.280
Or are you just working with
the data and having fun?

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:01.940
HILARY MASON: Well, it's all
of the above, actually.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:06.380
So we tend to ask a
research question.

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:10.465
And that might be something
like, can we build a model of

00:12:10.465 --> 00:12:11.840
canonical social sharing?

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:15.520
So is there a consistent way
that content is shared through

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:17.310
different social networks?

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:19.280
And so we'll go out and
say, OK, how do we

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:20.260
know when we've won?

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:22.270
How do we know when we've done
that, when we've actually

00:12:22.270 --> 00:12:23.530
answered that question?

00:12:23.530 --> 00:12:25.460
And then two, is it scalable?

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:28.870
So can we actually build
a system to do this?

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:31.480
Most of our products are
real-time analytics products.

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:33.960
So is it possible to do
this in real-time?

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.030
And then, if so, what should
the product look like?

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:40.410
And so that question was
actually not hypothetical.

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:43.490
It was what we spent most
of last year working on.

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:46.350
And we actually released an
experimental product called

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:50.420
Realtime, which is at the domain
rt.ly, where you can go

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:50.970
in and look.

00:12:50.970 --> 00:12:53.560
And it's showing you the stories
that are getting that

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:55.110
initial spike of attention.

00:12:55.110 --> 00:12:58.050
And you can now go in and
see the actual maps of

00:12:58.050 --> 00:13:00.010
attention over time.

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:03.030
So that's an example of
something that has gone from

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:06.220
research to infrastructure
to experiment.

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:09.100
And soon, to bitly product.

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:10.450
KATHRYN HURLEY: Awesome.

00:13:10.450 --> 00:13:13.100
It's always fun to see the work
that you do get put into

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:14.562
the product, I think.

00:13:14.562 --> 00:13:15.890
HILARY MASON: Absolutely.

