work around these things are

00:14:21.530 --> 00:14:25.530
to always talk to people
in a very positive way.

00:14:25.530 --> 00:14:31.470
So not to get frustrated or
upset but rather to say, OK,

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:32.400
here's our problem.

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:34.930
How do we solve this problem?

00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:37.080
And I'm really fortunate, again,
to work with a lot of

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:40.180
smart people who are
really nice.

00:14:40.180 --> 00:14:42.950
In fact, our number one hiring
rule has always been, don't

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:45.646
hire assholes.

00:14:45.646 --> 00:14:50.020
And so that tends to work
out pretty well.

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:50.550
KATHRYN HURLEY: That's
a good rule.

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:51.836
APRIL ANDERSON: Yes,
it's a good mantra.

00:14:51.836 --> 00:14:56.480
So Hilary, I would love to hear
more about your role and

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:57.710
some of those challenges.

00:14:57.710 --> 00:14:59.625
And also, some of those
opportunities as you work as

00:14:59.625 --> 00:15:01.540
the chief scientist at bitly.

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:05.780
How do you really balance
wearing the technical hat and

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:08.800
the technical aspects of your
role with the things that are

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:11.790
more business-oriented?

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:14.140
HILARY MASON: That's a really
good question because it's

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:16.820
something I'm still learning
how to do.

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:20.240
And when I started at bitly
three years ago, I was writing

00:15:20.240 --> 00:15:22.750
code every day.

00:15:22.750 --> 00:15:24.790
We were such a small team
that everyone knew what

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:25.640
everyone was doing.

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:27.110
And it was pretty clear
where we were going.

00:15:27.110 --> 00:15:31.340
We had only one thing to do,
and that was keep scaling.

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:34.330
And now we've got a couple of
different products, a larger

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:36.910
business, a lot more people.

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:40.250
And so it has been a challenge
to learn how to grow with the

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:43.130
company and to grow
my team from just

00:15:43.130 --> 00:15:47.530
me to now nine people.

00:15:47.530 --> 00:15:52.250
The ways I try to do that
are generally--

00:15:52.250 --> 00:15:54.790
it sounds really trite, but
actually applying the

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:56.020
scientific method.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:59.740
So even in product or business
problems saying,

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:01.070
OK, here's my theory.

00:16:01.070 --> 00:16:03.810
What experiments can we do
given the data we have

00:16:03.810 --> 00:16:06.320
available, or the people we
have available, or the

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:10.870
resources we have available
to answer this question?

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:13.210
Can we try something and see
what happens, and then try

00:16:13.210 --> 00:16:14.980
something else?

00:16:14.980 --> 00:16:17.870
And that is generally how I've
thought about the world.

00:16:17.870 --> 00:16:19.610
And it has worked pretty well.

00:16:19.610 --> 00:16:20.120
APRIL ANDERSON: That's great.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:22.710
And how do you really infuse
that with your team?

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:25.430
This is an industry and
certainly a product that

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:28.520
requires constant iteration,
constant innovation.

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:32.330
How do you really foster that
creativity with your teams?

00:16:32.330 --> 00:16:34.510
HILARY MASON: I try and
lead by example.

00:16:34.510 --> 00:16:38.540
And what I mean there is to
have lots of bad ideas.

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:41.430
Because you have to have
a lot of ideas to

00:16:41.430 --> 00:16:42.750
have any good ideas.

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:45.770
And if you don't even
try to articulate

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.410
those, the bad ones--

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:49.280
if you're afraid to do it
or you're going to be

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:51.520
embarrassed, then you're going
to miss out on the good ones.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:54.960
Or when you say something that
might not be the best idea,

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:56.670
maybe one of your colleagues
can say, well,

00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:57.910
that's total bullshit.

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:02.480
But this other twist on it
might actually work.

00:17:02.480 --> 00:17:05.010
And so we try and keep that
kind of open environment.

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:08.900
And also, keep in mind that a
lot of the best ideas don't

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:12.550
come from our researchers
with PhDs in math.

00:17:12.550 --> 00:17:15.010
They come from the people who
are working on our community

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:18.390
support team because they're
actually there working with

00:17:18.390 --> 00:17:20.490
customers all the time.

00:17:20.490 --> 00:17:23.130
And so within the company, we
try and create a culture that

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:24.349
ideas come from anywhere.

00:17:24.349 --> 00:17:25.720
Questions can come
from anywhere.

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:27.710
No one should be afraid
to have bad ones

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:31.080
or ask silly questions.

00:17:31.080 --> 00:17:33.590
Yeah, I do a lot of that.

00:17:33.590 --> 00:17:35.080
APRIL ANDERSON: No, I think it's
something we all kind of

00:17:35.080 --> 00:17:35.730
strive to do, right?

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:37.900
Keep that customer
voice infused in

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:39.490
everything that we do.

