00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:12.880
So you have a certain amount
of money, and you

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:14.080
watch that go up.

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:14.965
And that's great, right?

00:18:14.965 --> 00:18:16.640
Your problem's solved.

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:18.730
But for a lot of things,
it's not that simple.

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:23.180
So one of the projects I'm
working on is growing our

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:25.200
platform and working
on API design.

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:28.260
And we start to think about,
OK, what kind of platform

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:29.340
users do we want?

00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:33.050
How do we want to understand
their behavior on our system?

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:36.360
On the technical side-- if there
are any technical folks

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:37.920
in the audience--

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:40.700
we have a consistent development
metaphor within

00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:42.590
bitly for all our systems,
which is you

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:43.640
have a stream of data.

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:45.640
You have a queuing system.

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:48.200
You have queue readers that
read out of that queue.

00:18:48.200 --> 00:18:49.980
You have some kind
of API layer.

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:51.960
And you have an application.

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:55.620
And what that lets us do is take
those streams of data and

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:58.050
put them in places where we
can analyze them pretty

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:01.210
easily, or hang things off of
them that can fire events when

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:02.760
metrics happen.

00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:06.960
And so we track everything we
can in StatsD and Graphite.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:10.360
We also have our own dashboard
called the Aquarium.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:13.890
