no canonical statement of what
a data scientist does or even

00:23:42.060 --> 00:23:47.120
how you look at data in
a non-scientific way.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:48.350
And so we wrote this down.

00:23:48.350 --> 00:23:50.190
And it is, indeed, this--

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:51.510
you get data.

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:52.620
You scrub it.

00:23:52.620 --> 00:23:53.660
You model it.

00:23:53.660 --> 00:23:55.870
You analyze it and you interpret
it, or make it

00:23:55.870 --> 00:23:57.150
interpretable for
other people.

00:23:57.150 --> 00:23:59.910
It's pretty simple and
seems obvious now.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:03.990
But at the time, I hadn't seen
it written down like that.

00:24:03.990 --> 00:24:08.640
So for young data scientists who
want to start to explore,

00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:10.590
the first thing you
need is data.

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:14.210
And there's actually a lot
of data out there.

00:24:14.210 --> 00:24:15.610
A lot of it's public data.

00:24:15.610 --> 00:24:17.390
You can look at some of
the government data.

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:19.680
Even bitly has a public
data set of all

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:21.490
the 1.usa.gov clicks.

00:24:21.490 --> 00:24:23.945
So we powered the federal
government URL shortener.

00:24:23.945 --> 00:24:25.100
It's all public data.

00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:27.650
It's a good way to play with
social data if you're

00:24:27.650 --> 00:24:29.160
interested in that.

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:30.430
Or you can scrape it.

00:24:30.430 --> 00:24:32.700
So a lot of people do that.

00:24:32.700 --> 00:24:35.570
I just did a really fun little
side project where I scraped

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:38.030
all the menus for non-fast-food
restaurants in

00:24:38.030 --> 00:24:42.040
New York City, and then tried to
plot clusters of different

00:24:42.040 --> 00:24:42.920
restaurant types.

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:44.120
So I found Chinatown.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.843
And I found where you should
go for Thai food.

00:24:46.843 --> 00:24:50.190
It was all really to find better
cheeseburgers, which--

00:24:50.190 --> 00:24:52.100
this has mostly worked.

00:24:52.100 --> 00:24:53.490
But the data's out there.

00:24:53.490 --> 00:24:57.380
And so if you can think of a
question you would ask if you

00:24:57.380 --> 00:24:58.420
had some data.

00:24:58.420 --> 00:25:00.920
Or the other way around, so find
some data and then look

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:04.240
at it and try and see what
stands out to you.

00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:07.470
Then you can start looking
at different tools.

00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:09.140
You can even start in Excel.

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.820
So it's sort of a dirty secret,
but a lot of people do

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:13.890
great work in Excel.

00:25:13.890 --> 00:25:16.450
And when you move up from that,
you can go either to R

00:25:16.450 --> 00:25:19.150
if you're a statistician by
training or Python if you're

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:22.090
more a computer scientist.

00:25:22.090 --> 00:25:23.160
Load that data up.

00:25:23.160 --> 00:25:26.160
And especially if you're in an
environment like IPython with

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:28.470
